# One file per rule at `prompts/<rule_id>.yaml`.
# Each entry: {id, text, expected_fire?: bool, note?: str}.
#
# expected_fire = true  → on-target (rule SHOULD fire on this prompt)
# expected_fire = false → off-target (rule should NOT fire here; tests false-trigger)
# expected_fire defaults to true.
#
# For rules that fire every turn (e.g., a global "always rewrite the prompt"),
# omit all expected_fire: false entries — the off-target list ends up empty,
# which is fine.
#
# The off-target prompts are the hard set when they exist: they must share
# keywords or domain with on-target prompts but require different behavior.
# Easy negatives ("write a fibonacci function" for a communication rule)
# test nothing — see references/methodology.md for what discriminating
# negatives look like.
#
# Example below targets an english_rewrite rule.

- id: ot_001
  text: "ファイル全部をJSONに変換して"
  expected_fire: true
  note: "Mixed-language input; rule should produce an English rewrite at line 1."

- id: ot_002
  text: "give me a func that does the thing"
  expected_fire: true
  note: "Casual English; rule still applies — rewrite normalizes to clearer phrasing."

# An off-target example for a CONDITIONAL rule (uncomment if applicable):
#
# - id: nt_001
#   text: "Refactor the auth middleware to use JWT instead of sessions, focusing on token validation in src/auth/middleware.ts."
#   expected_fire: false
#   note: "Already in clean English — rewriting would be over-application."
